{
  "text": "It may be tempting to attribute the elevated risk of thromboembolic events to achieving pregnancy, as being pregnant results in a 10-fold increase in risk of venous thromboembolic events. [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] However, the true pathophysiology is likely multi-factorial. The literature shows that a fair minority of women with thromboembolic events secondary to IVF did not achieve pregnancy. [CITATION_3] Additionally, underlying thrombophilias were found in 41% of women who had venous thromboembolic events. [CITATION_4] These points would argue against pregnancy as the sole factor in developing a thrombus.",
  "correct_citation": {
